  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages:\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act in the US\n- Limited initial regulations\n- Primarily focused on financial reporting\n\n2. International Developments:\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created global anti-money laundering standards\n- Developed recommendations for international cooperation\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones:\n- 1990s: Enhanced reporting requirements\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Increased financial institution compliance obligations\n- Expanded suspicious activity reporting\n\n4. Modern Approaches:\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Risk-based assessment frameworks\n- Cryptocurrency transaction monitoring\n\n5. Recent Trends:\n- Stricter beneficial ownership disclosure\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Technology-driven compliance mechanisms\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. Emerging Focus Areas:\n- Digital currency regulations\n- Blockchain transaction tracking\n- Complex corporate structure transparency\n- Cross-border enforcement mechanisms\n\nThe legislation continues evolving to address emerging financial crime techniques and technological advancements.",
